  abstract = {Individuals engaged in outdoor activities are directly exposed to environmental parameters. In harsh microclimates these parameters may present various levels of physiological risks. Hence, it is important to evaluate such risks in association with the variation found in environmental parameters. With this in mind, this research aimed to investigate the possible thermal risks present in bike paths, which are important urban spaces by using thermal comfort indicators. The research was conducted in Balneario Camboriu, Santa Catarina state (SC), Brazil, in summertime, and sought to evaluate the proportion of bike paths that were affected by uncomfortable thermal conditions. The study employed Sky View Factor (SVF) and Local Climate Zone (LCZ), two physical indicators of urban areas, to choose the most thermally comfortable bike paths. The estimation of thermally comfortable conditions was conducted in two time points: early morning (9:00 AM) and late afternoon (4:00 PM). The findings showed that most of the studied bike paths were thermally uncomfortable early in the morning. However, in the late afternoon the level of thermal discomfort tended to gradually drop. Moreover, the analysis revealed that two key factors influencing the estimations of thermal comfort were the LCZ and the specific type of thermal comfort index employed in the study. The research findings provide a base for the development of thermally adaptive strategies directed at creating sustainable outdoor spaces that are conducive to activities such as cycling. These measures can potentially assist urban planning and design practices to enhance thermal comfort in outdoor environments, reducing thermal risks and thereby promoting more sustainable and inclusive outdoor activities.},
